# Why Are People Taking Ivermectin for COVID-19? An In-Depth Analysis

Since the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic, ivermectin, an antiparasitic drug with a long history of use in humans and animals, has attracted significant attention as a potential treatment or prophylactic agent against COVID-19. Despite widespread skepticism from the scientific and medical communities, many individuals have sought out ivermectin for COVID-19, often in the absence of robust clinical evidence supporting its efficacy. This report aims to provide a comprehensive, evidence-based analysis of the reasons behind the public’s use of ivermectin for COVID-19, drawing from a broad range of scientific literature, regulatory statements, and social phenomena observed during the pandemic.

---

## Background on Ivermectin

Ivermectin is an antiparasitic medication approved for use in humans for decades, primarily to treat parasitic infections such as onchocerciasis and strongyloidiasis, and in veterinary medicine for parasite control in animals ([Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivermectin_during_the_COVID-19_pandemic)). It has an excellent safety profile when used at approved doses, with billions of doses administered worldwide and a very low incidence of serious adverse events ([American Council on Science and Health, 2021](https://www.acsh.org/news/2021/05/04/who%E2%80%99s-afraid-ivermectin-15529)).

---

## Scientific and Clinical Context of Ivermectin for COVID-19

### Early Laboratory Evidence and Initial Enthusiasm

Interest in ivermectin as a COVID-19 treatment was initially sparked by in vitro studies demonstrating that ivermectin could inhibit the replication of SARS-CoV-2 in cell cultures. For example, a study published in *Antiviral Research* showed a 5,000-fold reduction in viral RNA at 48 hours post-treatment in vitro ([MSN, 2021](https://www.msn.com/en-us/health/medical/why-do-people-want-to-take-ivermectin-for-covid/ar-AAOr5R3)). This laboratory evidence led to hypotheses that ivermectin might have clinical utility against COVID-19.

However, experts quickly cautioned that in vitro efficacy does not necessarily translate to clinical effectiveness in humans, especially given the high doses required to achieve similar antiviral concentrations in vivo, which may not be safe or achievable ([MSN, 2021](https://www.msn.com/en-us/health/medical/why-do-people-want-to-take-ivermectin-for-covid/ar-AAOr5R3); [Inverse, 2021](https://www.inverse.com/science/ivermectin-drug-covid-19)).

### Clinical Trials and Evidence Limitations

A large number of clinical studies, including randomized controlled trials (RCTs), observational studies, and meta-analyses, have investigated ivermectin’s efficacy for COVID-19. However, many of these studies have been criticized for serious methodological limitations such as small sample sizes, heterogeneity in patient populations, variable dosing regimens, uncontrolled cointerventions, and high risks of bias ([BMJ Evidence-Based Medicine, 2021](https://ebm.bmj.com/content/early/2021/05/26/bmjebm-2021-111678); [Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivermectin_during_the_COVID-19_pandemic)).

Several high-profile studies initially reporting positive effects were later retracted due to concerns about data falsification, unverifiable data, or ethical violations ([Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivermectin_during_the_COVID-19_pandemic); [NPR, 2021](https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2021/09/19/1038369557/ivermectin-anti-vaccine-movement-culture-wars)). These retractions contributed to public confusion and polarized opinions.

Regulatory agencies including the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA), World Health Organization (WHO), European Medicines Agency (EMA), and national health bodies have consistently advised against the use of ivermectin for COVID-19 outside clinical trials due to insufficient evidence of efficacy and potential safety concerns ([Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivermectin_during_the_COVID-19_pandemic); [Inverse, 2021](https://www.inverse.com/science/ivermectin-drug-covid-19)).

---

## Reasons Why People Are Taking Ivermectin for COVID-19

Despite the lack of conclusive evidence and official warnings, many people continue to seek and use ivermectin for COVID-19. The reasons for this phenomenon are multifaceted and can be grouped into the following categories:

### 1. **Desperation and Search for Treatment Options**

At various points in the pandemic, especially early on and during surges, patients and clinicians faced limited treatment options for COVID-19. The urgent need for effective therapies, combined with the slow pace of vaccine rollout and antiviral development, led some to consider repurposed drugs like ivermectin as potential solutions ([TrialSite News, 2021](https://trialsitenews.com/fact-checking-the-fact-checkers-the-case-of-ivermectin-for-publicly-subsidized-research/); [MSN, 2021](https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/what-is-ivermectin-and-how-did-people-get-the-idea-it-can-treat-covid/ar-AAOibe2)).

Dr. David Boulware, an infectious disease expert, noted that ivermectin’s popularity partly reflects this desperation: people want a therapy and may latch onto any available option with some preliminary data, even if the evidence is weak or inconclusive ([MSN, 2021](https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/what-is-ivermectin-and-how-did-people-get-the-idea-it-can-treat-covid/ar-AAOibe2)).

### 2. **Misinformation and Social Media Amplification**

Ivermectin’s profile was significantly boosted by misinformation campaigns and social media advocacy. Groups such as the Front Line COVID-19 Critical Care Alliance (FLCCC) promoted ivermectin as a “miracle cure,” and their messaging went viral, especially among COVID-19 skeptics, anti-vaccination proponents, and conspiracy theorists ([Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivermectin_during_the_COVID-19_pandemic)).

High-profile media personalities and influencers, including some right-wing media figures and podcasters, publicly endorsed ivermectin, further amplifying its reputation despite the lack of scientific consensus ([NPR, 2021](https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2021/09/19/1038369557/ivermectin-anti-vaccine-movement-culture-wars)).

### 3. **Misinterpretation of Scientific Studies**

Many people outside the medical community have misunderstood or overinterpreted early laboratory findings and preliminary clinical data. The in vitro antiviral activity of ivermectin was often cited as evidence of clinical benefit, ignoring the pharmacokinetic challenges and lack of consistent clinical trial support ([MSN, 2021](https://www.msn.com/en-us/health/medical/why-do-people-want-to-take-ivermectin-for-covid/ar-AAOr5R3)).

Meta-analyses and systematic reviews that initially suggested benefit were later questioned or retracted due to data quality issues, but these nuances were often lost in public discourse ([Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivermectin_during_the_COVID-19_pandemic)).

### 4. **Distrust in Official Guidance and Government Agencies**

Distrust of government health agencies, pharmaceutical companies, and mainstream scientific consensus has fueled ivermectin’s appeal among certain groups. For some, ivermectin became a symbol of resistance against perceived overreach or censorship by authorities ([NPR, 2021](https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2021/09/19/1038369557/ivermectin-anti-vaccine-movement-culture-wars)).

This distrust was compounded by the politicization of COVID-19 measures, leading individuals to seek alternative treatments aligned with their ideological beliefs.

### 5. **Availability and Off-Label Use**

Ivermectin is widely available as a prescription drug for parasitic infections and is also used extensively in veterinary medicine. The availability of veterinary formulations, which are often more concentrated and not intended for human use, led some individuals to self-medicate with these products, sometimes resulting in poisoning or adverse effects ([MSN, 2021](https://www.msn.com/en-us/health/medical/why-do-people-want-to-take-ivermectin-for-covid/ar-AAOr5R3); [Inverse, 2021](https://www.inverse.com/science/ivermectin-drug-covid-19)).

The FDA issued warnings against using ivermectin intended for animals and emphasized that ivermectin is not authorized for COVID-19 treatment ([Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivermectin_during_the_COVID-19_pandemic)).

